# Open issue: drag-select copy clobbers scroll position

## TL;DR

In bui (Electron + xterm.js client over ssh+tmux to a remote running `claude`), drag-selecting in tmux's copy mode either copies-but-jumps-to-bottom OR stays-but-doesn't-copy. We want both: stay at scroll position AND clipboard updates.

## Current (working) state

`~/.tmux.conf` has the user's original binding:
```
bind-key -T copy-mode-vi MouseDragEnd1Pane send-keys -X copy-pipe-and-cancel "~/.local/bin/tmux-osc52"
bind-key -T copy-mode    MouseDragEnd1Pane send-keys -X copy-pipe-and-cancel "~/.local/bin/tmux-osc52"
```

`set -s set-clipboard off`. `set -g allow-passthrough on`. Tmux 3.4.

The `tmux-osc52` script (`~/.local/bin/tmux-osc52`) wraps OSC 52 in tmux's passthrough escape (`\033Ptmux;<doubled>\033\\`) and writes to `$(tmux display-message -p '#{pane_tty}')`. This works because:

1. `copy-pipe-and-cancel` runs the script with selection on stdin → script writes passthrough OSC 52 to pane TTY.
2. **`-and-cancel` exits copy mode**, which triggers a tmux pane redraw, which flushes the pane-output queue. Tmux processes the passthrough wrapper (allow-passthrough on), strips it, emits inner OSC 52 to clients.
3. xterm.js parses OSC 52 → our custom OSC handler decodes base64 → IPCs to Electron main → `clipboard.writeText` → Mac clipboard. Working.

But `-and-cancel`'s downside: the copy-mode exit jumps the viewport back to the bottom. User loses their scroll position after every selection.

## What we want

Same selection behavior, but viewport stays at scroll position after release. So:

- Keep clipboard write working (current state OK).
- Don't snap back to bottom after drag-end.

## What's been ruled out

| Attempt | Result |
|---|---|
| Switch binding to `copy-pipe-no-clear` | View stays ✓, clipboard breaks ✗ |
| Same + add `\; refresh-client` | View stays ✓, clipboard still breaks ✗ |
| Same + set `set-clipboard external` (so tmux emits OSC 52 itself, bypassing the pane-output queue entirely) | View stays ✓, clipboard still broke ✗ |
| Drop passthrough wrapping in script (write plain OSC 52) | Total clipboard break ✗ |

## Root cause hypothesis (verified)

While in copy mode, **tmux queues pane output** instead of processing/forwarding it immediately. The script's passthrough OSC 52 sits in the queue.

- `-and-cancel`: exits copy mode → tmux redraws → queue flushes → OSC 52 reaches clients.
- `-no-clear`: stays in copy mode → queue doesn't flush → OSC 52 never reaches clients.

`refresh-client` after the binding doesn't flush the pane-output queue (only the client display side).

`set-clipboard external` should make tmux emit its own OSC 52 directly to clients (bypassing the pane queue), but in our test that ALSO didn't reach. Worth re-investigating — maybe the test was bad.

## Things to try next

1. **Re-test `set-clipboard external` properly.** Do a clean test: switch to `copy-pipe-no-clear`, set `set-clipboard external`, drag-select, watch for `[osc52]` log in DevTools. If log appears immediately → tmux IS emitting; if not → tmux's set-clipboard emission is also gated on something else.

2. **Skip the script entirely with `set-clipboard external`.** With `set -s set-clipboard external`, tmux emits OSC 52 itself for any `copy-pipe*` command. Try:
   ```
   bind-key -T copy-mode-vi MouseDragEnd1Pane send-keys -X copy-selection-no-clear
   ```
   No script, just `copy-selection-no-clear`. Tmux should emit OSC 52 to clients automatically.

3. **Side-channel from the script via separate ssh.** Have the script copy the buffer text and write to clipboard via a side channel (e.g. write to a known file → bui's main process polls the file via separate SSH). Bypasses tmux output entirely.

4. **Do clipboard sync app-side instead of tmux-side.** Detect mouse-up in xterm (in mouse-mode, easier said than done), then immediately run `tmux show-buffer` via bui's control-plane SSH and write to clipboard. Loses the elegance of "let tmux do it" but is robust.

5. **Bounce out of copy mode and back.** Try chaining `copy-pipe-and-cancel "..." \; copy-mode -u` (or some variant) to enter copy mode again at the previous scroll position. Tmux doesn't natively preserve scroll position across copy-mode exit/re-enter, so this is unlikely to work without extra bookkeeping.

6. **Check if tmux 3.4 specifically has a bug here.** Newer tmux (3.5+) might have changed pane-output handling in copy mode.

My instinct: option **4** is the most pragmatic. Mouse-up detection in xterm with mouse mode active is a known wart but workable. Wraps the issue with bui-side logic instead of fighting tmux.

## Server side

- 157.90.224.92, user `dev`, tmux 3.4
- `~/.local/bin/tmux-osc52` — passthrough OSC 52 emitter (untouched, original)
- `~/.tmux.conf` — restored to original (with `copy-pipe-and-cancel`)
- `~/.tmux.conf.pre-bui` — backup snapshot from before any bui changes

## App side

- `src/renderer/Terminal.tsx` line ~75: custom OSC 52 handler is in place. Verified working when invoked directly via `_term.write(...)` in DevTools. Not the bottleneck.
- `src/main/pty.ts`: `tmuxConfigStatus` / `tmuxSetupConfig` / `tmuxRestoreConfig` infrastructure exists for bui-managed config; **not auto-invoked** (we removed the auto-call from `store.refresh()`).

## Reproduction

1. Start bui (npm run dev), attach to a project.
2. Wait for some scrollback to accumulate.
3. Scroll up with wheel (enters tmux copy mode).
4. Drag-select some text.
5. Observe: viewport snaps to bottom on release. Cmd+V into another app pastes selection ✓.
6. Switch binding to `copy-pipe-no-clear`. Repeat.
7. Observe: viewport stays at scroll position ✓. Cmd+V pastes nothing ✗.
